President Obama has announced his intent to nominate James F. Entwistle as Ambassador to the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Mimi E. Alemayehou as a member of the Board of Directors of the African Development Foundation, and Johnnie Carson as another member of the Board of Directors of the African Development Foundation. 

James F. Entwistle is currently the Deputy Chief of Mission at the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, Thailand. He has previous experience serving in various diplomatic roles in countries such as Sri Lanka, Central African Republic, and Malaysia. He also has experience working in Washington, D.C. in the Bureau of Intelligence and Research and the Bureau of African Affairs.

Mimi E. Alemayehou has been nominated to serve as Executive Vice President of the Overseas Private Investment Corporation. She has previously served as the United States Executive Director at the African Development Bank and has worked in various roles related to international development and trade. Alemayehou is a naturalized U.S. citizen, born in Ethiopia and raised in Kenya.

Johnnie Carson is currently the Assistant Secretary for African Affairs at the U.S. Department of State. He has a long career in the Foreign Service, including ambassadorships to Kenya, Zimbabwe, and Uganda. He also has experience working in various roles related to Africa at the National Intelligence Council and the National Defense University. Carson has a Bachelor of Arts in History and Political Science and a Master of Arts in International Relations.